 and also   Mabel .  It gained some currency from being borne by the character Amabel Rose Adams in  Angela Thirkell's  Barsetshire Chronicles (  1933  onwards)."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant of   Dev ."],"variants":[{"name":"Deborah","meanings":["Biblical name (meaning ‘bee’ in Hebrew), borne by the nurse of Rebecca (Genesis 35:8) and by a woman judge and prophet (Judges 4–5) who led the Israelites to victory over the Canaanites. It has always been popular as a Jewish name. It was in use among Christians by the mid 16th century and was taken up by the Puritans in the 17th century, in part because the bee was a symbol of industriousness. Since then it has enjoyed enormous popularity, peaking in the 1960s. Among other famous bearers is the actress  Deborah Kerr  (  1921–2007 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Lady Amabel de Plesley was born about 1165, in Branston, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Serlo III Pleasley ,of Ashover, was 25 and her mother, Matilda Unknown, was 21. She had at least 2 sons with Oliver de Eyncourt. She died in Blankney, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"about 1165–":"umbes 1165–Surnud","1144–Female":"1144–Surnud","1165–Female":"1165–Surnud","1168–1203":"1168–1203","1172–1202":"1172–1202","1150–1201":"1150–1201","1196–1246":"1196–1246","–Male":"Surnud","1142–1203":"1142–1203","1146–Female":"1146–Surnud","1165":"1165","1142":"1142","1196":"1196","1150":"1150","1172":"1172","1203":"1203","1246":"1246","1202":"1202","1146":"1146","1201":"1201","1168":"1168","1144":"1144","about 1167":"umbes 1167","about 1165":"umbes 1165","about 1196":"umbes 1196","Branston, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Branston, Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Blankney, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Blankney, Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Pleasley, Derbyshire, England":"Pleasley, De